The issue here stems from not escaping regex metacharacters. 

The [Replace][1] operator performs a regex match and replacement of the matched characters. `*` is a quantifier in regex, which will match zero or more characters of the current matched character (the character before the `*`). Regex will match `*` literally if it is backslash escaped, which becomes `\*`. You can also use the `Escape()` method from the Regex class on your string, which will escape the metacharacters automatically.

    $StringToReplace = &#39;&lt;logger name=&quot;\*&quot; minlevel=&quot;Trace&quot; writeTo=&quot;console&quot; /&gt;&#39;
    $StringReplacement = &quot;&lt;logger name=`&quot;*`&quot; minlevel=`&quot;$env:ai_logging_mode`&quot; writeTo=`&quot;console`&quot; /&gt;&quot;
    $_ -replace $StringToReplace,$StringReplacement

To use the Regex class `Escape()` method, you can do the following:

    $StringToReplace = [regex]::Escape(&#39;&lt;logger name=&quot;\*&quot; minlevel=&quot;Trace&quot; writeTo=&quot;console&quot; /&gt;&#39;)
    $StringReplacement = &quot;&lt;logger name=`&quot;*`&quot; minlevel=`&quot;$env:ai_logging_mode`&quot; writeTo=`&quot;console`&quot; /&gt;&quot;
    $_ -replace $StringToReplace,$StringReplacement


  [1]: https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.core/about/about_comparison_operators?view=powershell-6#replacement-operator

